      <elementaryExchange id="82624d13-9c4d-553f-9281-4033141598a9" unitId="487df68b-4994-4027-8fdc-a4dc298257b7" amount="2.1E-05" sourceId="13c07be7-5ae6-4105-8a2c-e63dfaf0e107" sourceYear="1996" sourceFirstAuthor="Bruck, M." elementaryExchangeId="21e46cb8-6233-4c99-bac3-c41d2ab99498">
        <name xml:lang="en">Particulate Matter, &lt; 2.5 um</name>
        <unitName xml:lang="en">kg</unitName>
        <comment xml:lang="en">Estimation, based on literature value. Total measured emissions within the system boundaries. It is assumed that the amount is 100% from combustion and therefore the share is calculated based on the emissions from the combustion. The share is based on EPA-Report: 75% of the total particulates.
A corresponding probing by an expert of the clay production industry has shown that the factor of 1.5 for CO2, CO, dust, NO2, SO2, and org. C is realistic (between 0.3 and 1.7). The source is based on the composition of the raw material clay which differs from the raw material which is used for brick.

Further references:
EPA (1998) Brick and Structural Clay Product Manufacturing, Emissions Factor Documentation for AP-42, Final Report, Section 11.3. EPA Contract 68-D2-0159, Work Assignment No. I-0, MRI Project No. 4601-01. U.S. Environmental Protection Agency (EPA), Office of Air Quality Planning and Standards, Research Triangle Park/NC, Online-Version under: &lt;http://www.epa.gov/ttn/chief/ap42/&gt;.

Weibel T. and Stritz A. (1995) Ökoinventare und Wirkungsbilanzen von Baumaterialien; Grundlagen für den ökologischen Vergleich von Hochbaukonstruktionen. In: ESU-Reihe Nr. 1/95. Laboratorium für Energiesysteme, Eidg. Technische Hochschule (ETH), Zürich.</comment>
        <uncertainty>
          <lognormal meanValue="2.1E-05" mu="-10.770988120240851" variance="0.35" varianceWithPedigreeUncertainty="0.44609999999999994"/>
          <pedigreeMatrix reliability="5" completeness="5" temporalCorrelation="5" geographicalCorrelation="3" furtherTechnologyCorrelation="3"/>
          <comment xml:lang="en">;</comment>
        </uncertainty>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">pm2.5</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">particles</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">particulates</synonym>
        <synonym xml:lang="en">pm</synonym>
